{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501420"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:29:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:29:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1760"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1760"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.13,0.1,0.56,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114828"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1760"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96832"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"928"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1341"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36633"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48267"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114828"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of palpitations one hour ago. He reports that these symptoms have been occurring intermittently for several months, but have become more frequent in the past three days. He denies any chest pain, dizziness, or syncope. He has no history of ischaemic heart disease or other significant medical conditions. He does not take any regular medications. He is a non-smoker and consumes alcohol occasionally. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is alert and oriented. His blood pressure is 130/70 mmHg, pulse rate is 120 beats per minute, respiratory rate is 16/min, and temperature is 36.7\u00b0C. His chest is clear on auscultation, and his jugular venous pressure is 3 cm above the sternal angle. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following options is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amiodarone","Carotid sinus massage","Electrical cardioversion","Metoprolol","Nifedipine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG above is consistent with atrial fibrillation (AF), indicated by the absence of P waves and an irregularly irregular rate of the QRS complexes. AF is a common type of tachyarrhythmia, and management depends on several factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf a patient is haemodynamically unstable, as indicated by hypotension or signs of end organ hypoperfusion (e.g. confusion, chest pain, hypoxia), unstable AF must be managed with urgent cardioversion. This can be done with medications (flecanide or amiodarone) or with direct current (DC) electrical cardioversion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the patient is stable, the timing of the patient\u0027s symptoms determine appropriate management. If AF is acute (generally \u0026lt;48 hours), it is safe to immediately initiate medications to achieve rate or rhythm control. If AF has lasted \u0026gt;48 hours, or duration of AF is unknown, the risk of thrombotic complications (e.g. stroke) is considered too high to start medications without evidence to the contrary. Hence, they require either:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA trans-oesophageal echocardiogram (TOE) to exclude a thrombus in the left atrium, or;\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnticoagulation for at least three weeks before cardioversion, to reduce the risk of stroke. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERate control is the preferred method for these patients (where thrombus cannot be ruled out or they are not anti-coagulated) until such time that cardioversion is considered safe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient is haemodynamically stable, as evidenced by a blood pressure of 130/70 mmHg and no signs of end-organ hypoperfusion, and does not require immediate \u003Cstrong\u003Eelectrical cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E. The duration of AF symptoms is more than 48 hours, which generally doesn\u0027t allow for safe initiation of treatment without the need for anticoagulation or trans-oesophageal echocardiogram (TOE) to rule out thrombus. Therefore, rate control is the preferred management over rhythm control due to the risk of stroke with either chemical or electrical cardioversion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial treatment in this scenario. It is a beta-blocker that helps control the ventricular rate in AF, providing symptomatic relief from palpitations. Rate control is often preferred in patients with a history of intermittent AF, as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid sinus massage\u003C/strong\u003E is not effective for AF and is typically used for other tachyarrhythmias like supraventricular tachycardia (SVT).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENifedipine\u003C/strong\u003E is a calcium channel blocker that acts peripherally and is not used for AF management. Centrally acting calcium channel blockers like diltiazem or verapamil are preferred for rate control in AF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E is not suitable for this patient due to the history and duration of AF. Medical cardioversion with amiodarone would require prior anticoagulation or a TOE to exclude thrombus risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Considerations when managing acute atrial fibrillation include haemodynamic stability and time frame since onset","It is a beta-blocker that helps control the ventricular rate in AF and may provide symptomatic relief from palpitations."],"references":["Atrial Fibrillation. In: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Wyse DG, Waldo AL, DiMarco JP, Domanski MJ, Rosenberg Y, Schron EB, et al. A comparison of rate control and rhythm control in patients with atrial fibrillation. N Engl J Med. 2002;347(23):1825-33. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12466506/","2024 ESC Guidelines for the management of atrial fibrillation developed in collaboration with the European Association for Cardio-Thoracic Surgery (EACTS"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96832"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1760"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21015"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21015"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Kqpg67LUvGCdWdxTt2K0xgK6AvqhET.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Kqpg67LUvGCdWdxTt2K0xgK6AvqhET.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":414}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96832"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17: